{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf28 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_synopsis_1}{\*\bkmkend co_synopsis_1}
{\b1 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb400 
Synopsis
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Defendant was convicted in the 240th Judicial District Court, Fort Bend County, C.A. Dickerson, J., of capital murder, and sentenced to death, and he appealed. The Court of Criminal Appeals, Teague, J., held that: (1) where defendant admitted his guilt at punishment phase of his capital murder prosecution, he waived any challenge to sufficiency of the evidence; (2) even without considering testimony of defendant\rquote s accomplice, evidence was sufficient to sustain verdict of conviction, and would permit a rational trier of fact to find guilt beyond a reasonable doubt; (3) defendant was not denied his right of confrontation by alleged failure to inform jury of any plea bargain agreements that existed between the prosecution and a codefendant, who testified for the State at trial; (4) fact that codefendant was sentenced to ten years\rquote  deferred probation for her participation in the abduction and murder of the victim did not mean that defendant\rquote s sentence of death was in violation of the 8th Amendment; and (5) if trial court erred by inserting phrase \u8220\'3for another\u8221\'3f in first special issue, such error was harmless beyond a reasonable doubt.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Affirmed.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Onion, P.J., and Clinton, J., concurred in the result.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
