{\b0 \qc \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb800 
OPINION
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
TEAGUE, Judge.
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B0011985113219_ID0EO5AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B0011985113219_ID0EO5AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B0011985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
*
}}}
\sa200 
\sb200 
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Roger De Garmo, aka Quinton Earl Combest, appellant, murdered Kimberley Anne Strickler, a young lady who was only twenty (20) years of age at the time of her untimely death. After finding appellant guilty of capital murder, the jury returned affirmative findings to special issues that were submitted to it by the trial judge pursuant to 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000172&cite=TXCMART37.071&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Art. 37.071(b), V.A.C.C.P
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Based upon the jury\rquote s answers, the trial judge assessed appellant\rquote s punishment at death.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Appellant was accompanied and assisted by an accomplice\u8212\'3fHelen Leydalia Mejia\u8212\'3fwhen he kidnapped and later murdered Strickler. Mejia testified for the State. As a result of a plea bargain agreement with the prosecution, but after appellant\rquote s trial, Mejia received ten (10) years\rquote  deferred probation for her participation in the abduction and murder of Strickler.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
We affirm appellant\rquote s conviction and sentence of death.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
We overrule appellant\rquote s challenge to the sufficiency of the evidence to sustain the jury\rquote s verdict finding him guilty of capital murder.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The record on appeal reflects that appellant and Mejia kidnapped Strickler in Harris County after she befriended them by giving them a ride in her automobile. Appellant later forced Strickler to get inside the trunk of her motor vehicle, after which he closed and locked the trunk lid. Later, after driving to a location in Fort Bend County, appellant opened the trunk lid of Strickler\rquote s vehicle. Acting with a state of mind which showed a heart regardless of social duty and fatally bent on mischief, appellant then deliberately and intentionally fired one bullet from a pistol into Strickler\rquote s head, which wound caused Strickler to die almost instantaneously. Because appellant intentionally murdered Strickler in the course of committing the offense of kidnapping, 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_713_660_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_713_660_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*660
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 he is guilty of capital murder. See 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000182&cite=TXPES19.03&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_d86d0000be040" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
V.T.C.A., Penal Code, Section 19.03(a)(2)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The record on appeal also reflects that shortly before appellant murdered Strickler, but after he and Mejia had kidnapped Strickler and stolen her automobile, and with Strickler inside of the locked trunk, but still alive, he and Mejia abducted John Moers, which abduction occurred after Moers had also befriended appellant and Mejia by helping them extricate Strickler\rquote s vehicle from its then stuck position. Mejia held Moers captive by pointing a pistol at him. With Mejia driving Strickler\rquote s vehicle, and Strickler still alive but inside of the locked trunk, and appellant driving Moer\rquote s pick-up, with Moers held hostage inside of the cab of his vehicle, appellant and Mejia changed their location. After arriving at the new location, which was out in the country, appellant opened the trunk lid and shot Strickler in the head which caused her death. Thereafter, Mejia drove Strickler\rquote s vehicle to another location, at which Strickler\rquote s vehicle, with Strickler\rquote s body in the trunk, was abandoned. With appellant now driving Moers\rquote  vehicle, Mejia sitting in the middle of the cab, and Moers sitting next to the passenger door, the parties proceeded to another location. During this drive, appellant told Moers, \u8220\'3fI will kill you too if you try anything, just don\rquote t try anything.\u8221\'3f Soon thereafter, Moers successfully escaped from appellant and Mejia by opening the passenger door and jumping from his vehicle.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As a result of what appears to have been extremely fine investigative work by several members of the Fort Bend County Sheriff\rquote s Department, who had been assigned the case after it had apparently been written off by other members of the Sheriff\rquote s Department as an unsolved murder, appellant and Mejia were eventually arrested.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F11985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[1]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B11985113219_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B11985113219_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Appellant\rquote s contention that the evidence is insufficient to sustain the jury\rquote s verdict finding him guilty of the capital murder of Strickler is totally without merit because at the punishment stage of the trial he testified and admitted killing Strickler. In so testifying, appellant intentionally, knowingly, and voluntarily rejected his attorneys\rquote  advice not to testify at the punishment stage of the trial, even though he had followed their advice at the guilt stage of the trial. Appellant told the members of the jury that they had made the right decision by finding him guilty of committing the capital murder of Strickler. He stated: \u8220\'3fI was the one that was there and I was the one that did the crime. So, now you can at least sleep well knowing that you picked the right person and not thinking you might not have ...\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
When he testified, appellant also threatened the jurors with death if they answered the special issues submitted to them in such a way that he, appellant, would only receive life imprisonment. He told the jurors that if that happened, i.e., that if he only received a life sentence, he would eventually, either acting individually or in conspiracy with others, cause each juror to die, or, if the juror was no longer alive, he would cause members of the juror\rquote s family to die. Appellant made no bones about what he intended to do if the jury\rquote s verdict did not result in him receiving the death penalty: \u8220\'3fI\rquote m not threatening, I\rquote m promising that if and when some catastrophe happens and I was put back on the street, if you are not available, somebody of your possession would be and I would just say my statement is you should give me the death penalty because that\rquote s the only way you\rquote re ever going to stop me because you have put me in this position ... I\rquote m going to die any way, so why not take with me some of the people that\rquote s going to make me die. That\rquote s the way I feel ... so you better ... put the \u8216\'3fYes\rquote  on both of them questions from my point of view.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
And the record reflects that the jurors did as appellant requested\u8212\'3fthey answered both special issues in the affirmative, which caused the death penalty to become the only penalty that the trial judge could assess.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F21985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[2]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B21985113219_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B21985113219_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F31985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[3]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B31985113219_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B31985113219_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In asserting that the evidence is insufficient to sustain the jury verdict finding him guilty of capital murder, appellant acknowledges that the present law in Texas 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_713_661_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_713_661_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*661
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 is that if a defendant does not testify at the guilt stage of the trial, but does testify at the punishment stage of the trial, and admits his guilt to the crime for which he has been found guilty, he has, for legal purposes, entered the equivalent of a plea of guilty. The law as it presently exists is clear that such a defendant not only waives a challenge to the sufficiency of the evidence, but he also waives any error that might have occurred during the guilt stage of the trial. In this instance, appellant unequivocally admitted his guilt to the capital murder of Strickler. We decline appellant\rquote s invitation to overrule the above principles of law regarding waiver of a challenge to the sufficiency of the evidence, and hold that because appellant admitted his guilt to the capital murder of Strickler, he waived any challenge to the sufficiency of the evidence. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1981125361&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Brown v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 617 S.W.2d 234 (Tex.Cr.App.1981)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1970138610&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Richardson v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 458 S.W.2d 665 (Tex.Cr.App.1970)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Also see the cases collected in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1982128579&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_724&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_sp_713_724" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Smyth v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 634 S.W.2d 721, 724 (Tex.Cr.App.1982)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (Teague, J., dissenting opinion); and see also 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1978134626&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_348&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_sp_713_348" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Bodde v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 568 S.W.2d 344, 348 (Tex.Cr.App.1978)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, in which this Court rejected the argument that a defendant was deprived of due process of law because he could not testify at the punishment hearing and admit his guilt without waiving any error that might have occurred during the guilt stage of the trial. This Court held: \u8220\'3fWe cannot say that this common-sense rule of procedure denied appellant due process of law.\u8221\'3f (348).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F41985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[4]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B41985113219_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B41985113219_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F51985113219_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[5]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B51985113219_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B51985113219_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Furthermore, it has long been the law of this State that in reviewing the sufficiency of the evidence, this Court will look to all of the evidence in the case that was adduced at both stages of the trial, and not just that offered or presented by the State. See 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1969135874&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_293&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_sp_713_293" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Davis v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 440 S.W.2d 291, 293 (Tex.Cr.App.1969)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1967132516&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Bellah v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 415 S.W.2d 418 (Tex.Cr.App.1967)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Thus, evidence presented at the punishment stage of the trial may be considered in determining whether the evidence is sufficient to sustain a guilty verdict for the primary offense. Compare 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1969137174&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_758&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_sp_713_758" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
