{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As we understand appellant\rquote s objection that he made in the trial court, his ground of error on appeal, and his argument thereunder, he is not complaining that he did not have sufficient notice in order to prepare against the accusation; we find, instead, that he is complaining that he did not have sufficient notice that at the punishment stage of the trial the State would establish that his conduct that caused Strickler\rquote s death could have occurred not only with the reasonable expectation of Strickler\rquote s death but that \u8220\'3fof another\u8221\'3f unnamed person as well. Appellant thus complains that the phrase \u8220\'3for another\u8221\'3f in the special issue permitted the jury to speculate that his causing Strickler\rquote s death was committed with the reasonable expectation that the death of a person other than Strickler would result. He asserts on appeal that because the evidence reflects that only Strickler could have been the reasonable object of his assault, inserting the phrase \u8220\'3for another\u8221\'3f causes the charge to become fundamentally erroneous. For authority, he cites 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1979106924&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Cumbie v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 578 S.W.2d 732 (Tex.Cr.App.1979)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, which was recently overruled by this Court in its decision of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1984107353&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Almanza v. State,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 686 S.W.2d 157 (Tex.Cr.App.1984)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, delivered March 6, 1985, to the extent that 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Cumbie
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 holds that any fundamental error requires \u8220\'3fautomatic\u8221\'3f reversal.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
We overrule appellant\rquote s third ground of error.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
However, had the jury not been required to first find beyond a reasonable doubt that appellant had deliberately caused the death of Strickler, which it did find beyond a reasonable doubt, and, secondly, had there been other evidence that would have supported or tended to support a finding that appellant caused Strickler\rquote s death with the reasonable expectation that the death of a person other than Strickler would result, 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_713_664_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_713_664_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*664
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 we believe that appellant\rquote s ground of error might have been meritorious.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The undisputed evidence, however, only supports the jury\rquote s affirmative finding that appellant\rquote s conduct that caused the death of Strickler was committed deliberately and with the reasonable expectation that the death of Strickler, 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
and no other person,
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 would result. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1983131952&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=Ic2428eb5e7bc11d9b386b232635db992&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_781&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.DocAnalysisJudicial)#co_pp_sp_713_781" }{\fldrslt 
